@flexiarg peeragogy/moderation
@title Throttle the Loud, Make Room for the Quiet, Reshape the Floor
@keywords power-law, participation, fishbowl, progressive-stack, stepping-back, equity-of-voice
@audience peer-learning facilitators, online-forum hosts
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/carrying-capacity peeragogy/heartbeat peeragogy/roles]

! conclusion: Online peer-learning participation reliably follows a power law — a few voices dominate, most lurk.  Moderation is the active counter-pressure on that distribution, performed both by the loudest participants throttling themselves and by the structure of the conversation reshaping who finds it cheap to speak.  Effective moderation operates on both the individual and the structural level; one without the other tends not to hold.
  + context: Voluntary online conversations skew toward those who type fastest, feel most confident, or have the most time.  Without counter-pressure, the resulting distribution silences the participants whose perspectives the group most needs to hear.  Moderation is not about silencing the loud; it is about restoring access for the quiet.  Techniques like the fishbowl (small-group reformat that depersonalises issues and reduces stress) and the progressive stack (queue ordering that prioritises voices heard less often) are structural moves; individual self-throttling — the dominant participant choosing to speak less — is the personal move.  Both are needed; either alone is fragile.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: depth-of-engagement ↔ breadth-of-voice.
    Real: the loud participants are often the engaged participants; throttling them risks losing the energy that keeps the conversation alive.  But unmoderated, that same energy crowds out the breadth of voice that makes a peer learning context peer-driven.
    Irreducible: a single conversation cannot simultaneously maximise depth from its most engaged voices and breadth across its quieter ones.  The moderator is choosing which to prioritise at each turn, even by inaction.
    Active: the pull recurs at every conversational turn, every thread, every meeting.  Moderation is a continuous activity, not a one-time configuration.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Self-throttle: the most active participants visibly hold back, ask questions instead of asserting, and let others answer first.  Names the dynamic without policing it.
    (2) Reformat to fishbowl: when a debate has become entrenched, restructure it as small-group conversations that depersonalise the issue and lower the cost of changing one's mind.
    (3) Progressive stack: order speakers by how recently and how often they have spoken, prioritising voices heard less.  Makes turn-taking a structural property, not a social negotiation.
    (4) Lower the floor: rewrite the prompt or the surface so quieter participants find a cheaper entry — shorter messages, smaller commitments, async options.  Reshapes who finds the conversation accessible.
    (5) Name the dynamic: surface the participation distribution explicitly ("we've heard mostly from X, Y, Z this week") so the group can adjust collectively rather than relying on individual heroics.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the participation distribution stays meaningfully closer to balanced than the unmoderated baseline, and quiet participants report that entry feels accessible.  Failing when: the conversation pattern locks into a small-group exchange while everyone else watches, or moderation is treated as a one-time setting rather than an ongoing practice.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Same-five-voices: every thread is dominated by the same handful of participants and the rest go silent.
    - Newcomer drop-off: new arrivals attempt one contribution, get no traction in the existing discussion shape, and leave.
    - Adversarial lock-in: a debate hardens into entrenched positions because no one re-formats the conversation to reduce the personal cost of changing position.
    - Silent dissent: disagreement migrates to back-channels because the main forum is too costly for quieter voices to enter.
